properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Weather Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Winter Weather Travel Advisory in effect for this evening. A band of heavy snow will continue to cross the region this evening resulting in poor visibility at times. A quick 5 cm of snow accumulation will be possible for most areas. However, areas from near Bancroft to Perth to the St. Lawrence River could see amounts in the 5 to 10 cm range before the snow comes to an end tonight. Travel is expected to be hazardous due to very poor visibility and rapidly accumulating snow on roadways as the heaviest band passes. In particular, travel along Highway 401 will be hazardous during the heaviest snow. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Smog Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Atmospheric conditions could result in a deterioration in air quality. High levels of air pollutants will persist until Wednesday morning. ### Smog especially affects asthmatic children and people with respiratory ailments or heart disease. It is therefore recommended that these individuals avoid intense physical activity outdoors until the smog warning is lifted. In Quebec, wood heating is the main source of fine particles that contribute to smog during winter. This activity generates the largest number of these particulates, more than industrial activities and transportation. Additional information: To learn more about the Info-Smog program, go to Environment Canada’s website at www.canada.ca/info-smog-program. For air quality indexes in Quebec, visit the website of the Ministère de l'Environnement et de la Lutte contre les changements climatiques at www.iqa.environnement.gouv.qc.ca/contenu/index_en.asp. For the air quality index in Montréal, visit the Réseau de surveillance de la qualité de l’air de la Ville de Montréal’s website at www.rsqa.qc.ca (french only). To learn more about the effects of smog on your health in Québec, visit the Ministère de la Santé et des Services sociaux’s website at www.quebec.ca/en/health. You can also visit the Direction régionale de santé publique du CIUSSS du Centre-Sud-de-l’Île-de-Montréal at www.santemontreal.qc.ca/en/public. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
Expires: 2021-01-27T14:59:05-00:00

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Extreme cold wind chills of minus 40 or colder continue in parts of southern Saskatchewan and southern Manitoba this morning. An Arctic ridge of high pressure continues to give frigid temperatures to portions of the southern prairies. Temperatures in the minus thirties along with winds of 10 to 15 km/h will produce extreme cold windchills of minus 40 or colder. Some moderation will occur later this morning but these wind chill values could resume one last time over sections of the Interlake and/or eastern Manitoba tonight into Thursday morning. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. For more information on cold and your health, visit Manitoba Health at https://www.gov.mb.ca/health/publichealth/environmentalhealth/cold.html or call Health Links - Info Santé at 204-788-8200 or toll-free at 1-888-315-9257. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Extreme wind chill values near minus 40 are expected early this morning and again tonight into Thursday morning. A cold arctic airmass will continue to give frigid temperatures to portions of northwestern Ontario. Temperatures in the minus thirties along with winds of 5 to 10 km/h will result in wind chill values near minus 40 this morning. Similar temperatures and wind chills are expected tonight into Thursday morning. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of about 5 cm is expected. Wet snow near 5 cm expected for inland sections tonight. Precipitation associated with an offshore low has developed over East Vancouver Island. While precipitation will stay as rain or wet snow along the immediate coast, snowfall near 5 cm is expected for some inland areas tonight. As the low moves southward Wednesday morning, the snow will ease. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Extreme cold will return in parts of southern Saskatchewan and southern Manitoba tonight. Wind chills of minus 40 or colder will return this evening and moderate by Wednesday morning. An Arctic ridge of high pressure continues to give frigid temperatures to the southern prairies. Temperatures in the minus thirties along with winds of 10 to 15 km/h will produce extreme cold windchills of minus 40 or colder. Some moderation will occur on Wednesday. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of about 10 cm is expected. Snowfall of 10 cm expected near the summit tonight. Precipitation associated with an offshore low has developed over the Malahat Highway. While precipitation will stay as rain or wet snow near sea level, snowfall of 10 cm is expected near the summit tonight. As the low moves southward Wednesday morning, the snow will ease. ### Weather in the mountains can change suddenly resulting in hazardous driving conditions. Road conditions are available at www.drivebc.ca. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. Extreme cold wind chills of minus 40 or colder continue in parts of southern Saskatchewan and southern Manitoba this morning. An Arctic ridge of high pressure continues to give frigid temperatures to portions of the southern prairies. Temperatures in the minus thirties along with winds of 10 to 15 km/h will produce extreme cold windchills of minus 40 or colder. Some moderation will occur later this morning but these wind chill values could resume one last time over sections of the Interlake and/or eastern Manitoba tonight into Thursday morning. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Extreme wind chill values near minus 45 are expected early this morning. A cold arctic airmass has allowed temperatures to drop into the minus thirties early this morning. These temperatures along with winds of 5 to 10 km/h will result in wind chill values near minus 45. Similar temperatures and wind chills may occur again tonight into Thursday morning. ### Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.
